1️⃣ Cluster & Nodes
kubectl get nodes
kubectl describe node <node-name>
kubectl get componentstatuses

Check:

Node Ready / NotReady

DiskPressure / MemoryPressure

SchedulingDisabled
_________________________________________________
2️⃣ Pod-Level Troubleshooting (MOST IMPORTANT)
Pod Status
kubectl get pods -A
kubectl get pod <pod-name> -o wide

Pod Details (First Command in Any Issue)
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

Look for:

Events

Scheduling errors

Image pull errors

Probe failures
______________________________________
3️⃣ Logs (Application Issues)
kubectl logs <pod-name>
kubectl logs <pod-name> --previous
kubectl logs <pod-name> -c <container-name>

Use when:

CrashLoopBackOff

App crashes

DB connection issues
___________________________________
4️⃣ Scheduling Issues (Pod Pending)
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
kubectl get nodes
kubectl describe node <node-name>
kubectl get pvc

Check:

Resource availability

Node affinity / taints

PVC bound or not
_________________________________________________
5.Image Issues
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
kubectl get secret

Check:

Selector mismatch

TargetPort mismatch

Pod readiness
______________________
7️⃣ Ingress Issues
kubectl get ingress
kubectl describe ingress <ingress-name>
kubectl logs <ingress-controller-pod>

Check:

TLS config

Path rules

Backend service mapping
______________________________________
8️⃣ Resource & Performance Issues

kubectl top nodes
kubectl top pods
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

Check:

CPU throttling

Memory OOMKilled

Missing requests
________________________________
9️⃣ HPA Issues
kubectl get hpa
kubectl describe hpa
kubectl top pods

Check:

Metrics server

CPU requests defined

HPA min/max limits
)__________________________
Storage Issues
kubectl get pv
kubectl get pvc
kubectl describe pvc <pvc-name>

Check:

PVC Pending

Access modes

StorageClass
__________________________
1️⃣1️⃣ Namespace & Quota Issues

kubectl get ns
kubectl get resourcequota
kubectl describe resourcequota

______________________________________
1️⃣2️⃣ Node Maintenance
kubectl cordon <node-name>
kubectl drain <node-name> --ignore-daemonsets --delete-emptydir-data
kubectl uncordon <node-name>

_________________________________________
“First I check pod status, then describe the pod, check logs, then verify node resources, services, and HPA depending on the issue.”
_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
